cards.description:
Describes the location of a resource in terms of it's postal address.
Number in Road or Street
Road or Street Name
Locality
Postal Code

Links to the physical resource through an E53 Place class
cards.helptext:
Number or Name

Use for the number or name of the house or building. For flats or subdivisions of a building use the number/name of the flat/subdivsion followed by the Number or Name of the building e.g. "Flat 15, Carlisle House or "Finance Department, Historic England".

Road or Street Name

Use for the main thoroughfare on which the building sits. Where a building is situated on the corner of 2 roads consider entering mutliple addresses.

Locality

Use for areas identified formally or informally by a particular name where people live or where certain activities take place that may form part of a town, city or urban area.

Town or City

Use for the main postal Town or City in which the building is located. Also includes hamlets and villages.

Postal Code

Use for the postcode of the property, where known.

graph.description:
This includes buildings (both ruined and in use), shipwrecks and aircraft crash sites, as well as field monuments such as barrows and field systems, wetlands, cropmarks, submerged landscapes, urban strata and find-spots typically associated with archaeology. The focus is on the ‘thing’ itself in this Information Group. Records of investigation of these features (e.g. archaeological excavations) are covered by Information Groups in the Activity theme.
The broad definition of monument extends to the recording of the former existence of buildings or archaeological remains now destroyed (e.g. by quarrying or urban development). The knowledge of these sites contributes to the overall understanding of the historic environment.
graph.name: Heritage Assets
